  "doc_id": "37503",
  "text": "Ongoing, case-control sampling and interviewing of birth defect cases are being conducted by states with birth defects registries (41) . These studies are including questions on the maternal interview concerning water consumption habits at home and at the workplace and linking water utility monitoring data to maternal address during the first trimester. An important limitation to these studies is the length of time, usually several months, between the child's birth and the maternal interview. Prospective cohort studies similar to the California prospective study of spontaneous abortions [CITATION_1] do not have this limitation. However, because birth defects are rare events, prospective cohort studies are not feasible for individual states to conduct. Discussion is currently underway to conduct a largescale, national longitudinal study enrolling children prenatally during the first trimester and following them through adolescence. Such a study should have drinking water exposures and adverse birth outcomes as an important component.",
